{"metadata":{"kernelspec":{"name":"ir","display_name":"R","language":"R"},"language_info":{"name":"R","codemirror_mode":"r","pygments_lexer":"r","mimetype":"text/x-r-source","file_extension":".r","version":"4.0.5"}},"nbformat_minor":4,"nbformat":4,"cells":[{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# Introduction\n\nCyclistic is a bike-share company based in Chicago, and they aim to design marketing strategies based on consumer behavior differences between casual riders, who purchase single-ride or full-day passes, and Cyclistic members, who hold annual memberships. The analysis below will uncover these differences to provide insights for converting casual riders into Cyclistic members (i.e. annual members).\n\nThe format for this notebook follows google's data analysis life cycle: ask, prepare, process, analyze, share, and act. \n\n","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# Ask Phase \nThe following questions are used to help guide the analysis:\n> * How do annual members and casual riders use Cyclistic bikes differently?\n> * What is the problem that needs to be solved?\n> * How can the insights drive business decisions? \n> * What is the business task?\n> * Who are the stakeholders?\n\nThe primary objective is to convert casual riders into Cyclistic members. To design an effective marketing strategy, we need to understand the distinctions between these two customer groups. **Therefore, our business task is to comprehend these differences via consumer insights to craft marketing strategies that target casual riders to become Cyclistic members.** This must also meet the needs of my stakeholders: Cyclistic's Executive Team and the Director of Marketing. ","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# Prepare Phase\n**For the current analysis, we have utilized a years worth of data collected from August 2022 through July 2023. This timeframe was chosen as it provides the most current and reliable dataset available, incorporating updated data elements such as the types of bikes used.** Using Cyclistic’s historical trip data helped identify differences between customer types: members and casual riders. The dataset is a result of concatenated monthly datasets that are available on Kaggle. It has been made available by Motivate International Inc. under a license.\n\nThe preceeding questions are used to assess and prepare the data for analysis: \n> * How is the data organized? \n> * Are there issues with bias and credibility in this data? Does your data ROCCC? \n> > Reliable, original, comprehensive, current, and cited. \n> * How are you addressing licensing, privacy, security, and accessibility?\n> * How did you verify the data’s integrity?\n> * How does it help you answer your question?\n> * Are there any problems with the data?\n\nThe database uses a wide structured format with the same amount of data elements. There is a single text file containing the metadata for every trip and the station table. The data exhibits some sampling bias as it cannot confirm whether casual riders have purchased multiple 24-hour passes, which may result in an overestimation. However, the data annual members and the frequency of service usage over time is credible and reliable since its 1st party, making it original, comprehensive, current, and well-cited. Customers’ personally identifiable information is not included for the purpose of data-privacy and is securely stored with the owner of the data. Trips(i.e. rows) are removed if there was incomplete data or if it is a duplicate to ensure data integrity.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# Process Phase\nGuiding question: What tools are you choosing and why?\n\nR is useful during data preprocessing, statistical analysis, and visualization tasks for large datasets. The following packages help with with data import, tidying, manipulation, and data visualization. As well as making date-time data easier to worth with. Using R's functions, the data elements consistency are examined using the functions below. \n\nAlso an [accessible color palette generator](https://venngage.com/tools/accessible-color-palette-generator) that is WCAG compliant for the graphs.\n","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"#load packages \nlibrary(tidyverse) #data import and wrangling\nlibrary(lubridate) #date-time functions \nlibrary(ggplot2)  #visualize data\n\n#upload data\ntrip_data <- read_csv(\"/kaggle/input/cyclistic-google-capstone-data/trip_data.csv\")\n\n\n#inspecting data frame\ncolnames(trip_data)  #column names list\nnrow(trip_data)  #amount of rows \ndim(trip_data)  #dimensions of data frame\nhead(trip_data)  #prev the first six rows. \nstr(trip_data)  #list of columns with the data types \nsummary(trip_data)  #statistical summary of data","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-09-27T07:00:33.550463Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-09-27T07:00:33.555099Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-09-27T07:01:22.911658Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Guiding questions: \n> * Have you ensured your data’s integrity?\n> * What steps have you taken to ensure that your data is clean?\n\nThe cleaning functions are saved to a different dataframe prevent the original data frame being corrupted. The pipe below removes na's and duplicates to ensure data integrity. Afterwards the number of rows removed from the cleaning functions is calculated. ","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"#removing na's and dups \ntrip_data_cleaned <- trip_data %>%\n  na.omit() %>%\n  distinct()\n\n#number of rows removed from trip_data\noriginal_rows <- nrow(trip_data)\nrows_removed <- original_rows - nrow(trip_data_cleaned)\nprint(rows_removed) ","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-09-27T07:01:22.914807Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-09-27T07:01:22.947868Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-09-27T07:01:34.276392Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Additional data elements are established to enrich insights for the business task. This changes the dimension of *trip_data_cleaned* because there are additional columns by breaking down the *started_at* field into:\n> * date (currently the default format is yyyy-mm-dd)\n> * month \n> * day\n> * year  \n> * day of the week (further organized as shown below)\n> * season \n\nThe final data element is *ride_duration* calculates the duration of the ride by finding the difference between *ended_at* and *started_at* fields.\n\n\nGuiding question: How can you verify that your data is clean and ready to analyze? \n\nIf the duration of the ride less than zero or assessed for quality by Cyclistic, the entire row will be removed. Lastly, the structure of the columns are inspected and generate a preview of the new data frame to verify that the new and existing data elements correspond with an appropriate data type.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"#adding columns that list the date, month, day, year of each ride and start time\ntrip_data_cleaned$date <- as.Date(trip_data_cleaned$started_at)\ntrip_data_cleaned$month <- month(trip_data_cleaned$started_at)\ntrip_data_cleaned$day <- day(trip_data_cleaned$started_at)\ntrip_data_cleaned$year <- year(trip_data_cleaned$started_at)\ntrip_data_cleaned$day_of_week <- format(trip_data_cleaned$started_at, \"%A\")\ntrip_data_cleaned$season <- case_when(\n  trip_data_cleaned$month %in% 3:5 ~ \"Spring\",\n  trip_data_cleaned$month %in% 6:8 ~ \"Summer\",\n  trip_data_cleaned$month %in% 9:11 ~ \"Autumn\",\n  TRUE ~ \"Winter\"\n)\n\n#organizing day of the week \ntrip_data_cleaned$day_of_week <- ordered(trip_data_cleaned$day_of_week, levels=c(\"Sunday\", \"Monday\", \"Tuesday\", \"Wednesday\", \"Thursday\", \"Friday\", \"Saturday\"))\n\n#organizing seasons\ntrip_data_cleaned$season <- ordered(trip_data_cleaned$season, levels=c(\"Spring\", \"Summer\", \"Autumn\", \"Winter\"))\n\n#create and calculate ride_duration in minutes\ntrip_data_cleaned$ride_duration <- as.numeric(difftime(trip_data_cleaned$ended_at,trip_data_cleaned$started_at)/60)\n\n#removing bad data, a few hundred entries when bikes were taken out of docks and checked for quality by Cyclistic or ride_duration was negative:\ntrip_data_cleaned <- trip_data_cleaned[!(trip_data_cleaned$start_station_name == \"HQ QR\" | trip_data_cleaned$ride_duration<0),]\n\n#inspect structure and generate preview\nstr(trip_data_cleaned)\nhead(trip_data_cleaned)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-09-27T07:01:34.279501Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-09-27T07:01:34.281099Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-09-27T07:01:46.864252Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# Analyze Phase\n","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Before the descriptive analysis begins to uncover insights regarding differences between casual riders and Cyclistic members, the following guiding questions are addressed: \n> * How should you organize your data to perform analysis on it?\n> * Has your data been properly formatted?\n\nThe dataframe presented above is structured as wide data post-data-tranformation, and it has been saved as a .csv file below. This organization makes it more convenient to identify and compare columns, and each column corresponds to its appropriate data type. The data is well-formatted, with each row representing a data subject and multiple columns containing various attributes of the data subject. \n\nThese are the guiding questions for the proceeding analysis:\n> - What surprises did you discover in the data?\n> - What trends or relationships did you find in the data?\n> - How will these insights answer your business questions?","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"trip_data_cleaned %>%\n  write_csv(\"trip_data_analysis.csv\")","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-09-27T07:01:46.867692Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-09-27T07:01:46.869508Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-09-27T07:02:52.670776Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"### Descriptive Analysis \n#### ⭐ All Data Elements\nConfirming each data element is properly formatted.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"summary(trip_data_cleaned) ","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-09-27T07:02:52.676177Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-09-27T07:02:52.678016Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-09-27T07:03:00.915742Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"#### ⭐ Amount of Casual Riders and Cyclistic Members\nIn the initial summary, the number 4,340,302 below *member_casual* is a number without context regarding the amount of casual riders and members. **However, the tibble below reveals that Cyclistic members make up a larger proportion, accounting for 63%, compared to casual riders, who represent 37%.** It is also visually conveyed through the bar graph with counts.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"trip_data_cleaned %>%\n  count(member_casual) %>%\n  rename(member_casual_count = n) %>%\n  mutate(percentage = round((member_casual_count / sum(member_casual_count)) * 100))","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-09-27T07:03:00.919352Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-09-27T07:03:00.921269Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-09-27T07:03:01.123416Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":"ggplot(trip_data_cleaned, aes(member_casual, fill = member_casual)) +\n    geom_bar() +\n    labs(x = \"User Type\", y = \"Count\", fill = \"User Type\", title = \"Amount of Casual Riders and Cyclistic Members\", tag = \"Figure 1\", caption = \"Data Source: Motivate International Inc.\") +\n    scale_y_continuous(labels = function(y) format(y, scientific = FALSE)) +\n    annotate(geom = \"text\", x = c(1,2), y = c(1650000, 2770000), label = c(\"1609215\", \"2731087\")) +\n    scale_fill_manual(values = c(\"casual\" = \"#e2bc2d\", \"member\" = \"#b067ce\"))","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-09-27T07:03:01.127058Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-09-27T07:03:01.128907Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-09-27T07:03:16.832037Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"#### → By Season\n**When comparing the counts and percentages between casual riders and Cyclistic members by season, Cyclistic members consistently ride more.** Also, Cyclistic users exhibit similar seasonal trends, with counts following this order from lowest to highest: winter, spring, fall, and summer. This can be attributed to the winter weather conditions in Chicago that make it difficult to use Cyclistic services.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"summary(trip_data_cleaned$season)\n\ntrip_data_cleaned %>%\n  group_by(season) %>%\n  count(member_casual) %>%\n  rename(count = n) %>%\n  mutate(percentage = round((count / sum(count)) * 100))","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-09-27T07:03:16.836689Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-09-27T07:03:16.838582Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-09-27T07:03:17.240903Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":"ggplot(trip_data_cleaned, aes(season, fill = member_casual)) +\n    geom_bar(position = \"dodge\") +\n    labs(x = \"Season\", y = \"Count\", fill = \"User Type\", title = \"Amount of Casual Riders and Cyclistic Members by Season\", tag = \"Figure 2\", caption = \"Data Source: Motivate International Inc.\") +\n    scale_y_continuous(labels = function(y) format(y, scientific = FALSE)) +\n    scale_fill_manual(values = c(\"casual\" = \"#e2bc2d\", \"member\" = \"#b067ce\"))","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-09-27T07:03:17.244525Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-09-27T07:03:17.246272Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-09-27T07:03:26.291567Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"#### ⭐ Casual Riders and Cyclistic Members Most Used Bike Type\nThe graph generated by the pipeline below presents the bike type count by user type to investigate potential differences in bike usage. Both casual riders and Cyclistic members predominantly use classic bikes. **However, when comparing the count of classic bikes to electric bikes, Cyclistic members favor classic bikes more than electric ones. In contrast, the difference in bike usage between classic bikes and electric bikes for casual riders is not as pronounced. Additionally, casual riders have a higher usage of docked bikes, as there are no instances of Cyclistic members using docked bikes.**","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"trip_data_cleaned %>%\n  group_by(member_casual,rideable_type) %>%\n  count(rideable_type) %>%\n  rename(counts = n)%>%\nggplot(aes(x = member_casual, y = counts, fill = rideable_type)) +\n    geom_col(position = \"dodge\") + \n    labs(x = \"User Type\", y = \"Count\", fill = \"Bike Type\", title = \"Bike Type Usage\", tag = \"Figure 3\", caption = \"Data Source: Motivate International Inc.\") +\n    scale_fill_manual(values = c(\"classic_bike\" = \"#e2bc2d\",\"electric_bike\" = \"#b067ce\", \"docked_bike\" = \"#30b0b5\")) ","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-09-27T07:03:26.294758Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-09-27T07:03:26.296378Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-09-27T07:03:27.118842Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"The descriptive statistics:","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"trip_data_cleaned %>%\n  group_by(member_casual,rideable_type) %>%\n  count(rideable_type) %>%\n  rename(counts = n)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-09-27T07:03:27.122084Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-09-27T07:03:27.123732Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-09-27T07:03:27.580168Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"#### ⭐ Day_of_the_week Usage by Casual Riders and Cyclistic Members\nThe dataframe and the bar graph depicts the count of casual riders and Cyclistic members by the day of the week. **A distinction arises between casual riders and Cyclistic members based on their usage patterns: casual riders tend to utilize Cyclistic more frequently on weekends, whereas Cyclistic members use it more for riding during weekdays.**","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"summary(trip_data_cleaned$day_of_week)\n\ntrip_data_cleaned %>%\n  group_by(day_of_week) %>%\n  count(member_casual) %>%\n  rename(counts = n)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-09-27T07:03:27.583438Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-09-27T07:03:27.585207Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-09-27T07:03:28.000381Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":"ggplot(trip_data_cleaned, aes(day_of_week, fill = member_casual)) +\n    geom_bar() +\n    labs(x = \"Day of the Week\", y = \"Count\", fill = \"User Type\", title = \"Weekly Usage by Casual Riders and Cyclistic Members\", tag = \"Figure 4\", caption = \"Data Source: Motivate International Inc.\") +\n    scale_y_continuous(labels = function(y) format(y, scientific = FALSE)) +\n    scale_fill_manual(values = c(\"casual\" = \"#e2bc2d\", \"member\" = \"#b067ce\")) +\n    facet_wrap(~member_casual)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-09-27T07:03:28.008329Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-09-27T07:03:28.010565Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-09-27T07:03:39.254562Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"### Data Dispersion\n#### ⭐ Members and Casual Rider's Ride Durations\nTo contextualize the *ride_duration* variable, the pipe removes outliers by excluding the lowest 5% and highest 5% of values. **The statistical summary and the corresponding graph reveal that casual riders tend to have longer ride durations on average, with greater variability compared to Cyclistic members, as shown by differences in means and interquartile ranges (IQR). Also there are more outliers for Cyclistic members.** Given that the IQR for each member type overlap, it is unlikely that the difference is statistically significant. ","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"trip_data_cleaned %>%\n    group_by(member_casual) %>%\n    summarise(\n        min = min(ride_duration, trim = 0.05),\n        q25 = quantile(ride_duration, 0.25, trim = 0.05),\n        median = median(ride_duration, trim = 0.05),\n        mean = mean(ride_duration, trim = 0.05),\n        q75 = quantile(ride_duration, 0.75, trim = 0.05),\n        max = max(ride_duration, trim = 0.05),\n        iqr = q75 - q25\n    )\n\n#calculating the 5th and 95th percentiles\nlower_quantile <- quantile(trip_data_cleaned$ride_duration, probs = 0.05)\nupper_quantile <- quantile(trip_data_cleaned$ride_duration, probs = 0.95)\n\n#filter the data to keep values within the desired range\ntrimmed_df <- trip_data_cleaned %>%\n  filter(trip_data_cleaned$ride_duration >= lower_quantile, trip_data_cleaned$ride_duration <= upper_quantile)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-09-27T07:03:39.257802Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-09-27T07:03:39.259428Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-09-27T07:03:40.789725Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":"ggplot(data = trimmed_df, aes(x = member_casual, y = ride_duration, fill = member_casual)) +\n    geom_boxplot() +\n    labs(x = \"User Type\", y = \"Time in Minutes\", fill = \"User Type\", title = \"Distribution of Ride Duration\", tag = \"Figure 5\", caption = \"Data Source: Motivate International Inc.\") +\n    scale_y_continuous(labels = function(y) format(y, scientific = FALSE)) +\n    scale_fill_manual(values = c(\"casual\" = \"#e2bc2d\", \"member\" = \"#b067ce\"))","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-09-27T07:03:40.792676Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-09-27T07:03:40.794209Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-09-27T07:03:57.061338Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"#### → By Day of the Week\nThe descriptive statistics below show **Cyclistic Members maintain shorter ride duration averages throughout the week whereas casual riders have longer ride duration averages based on the means. Averages for both types of users are higher on weekends compared to the weekdays.** Similar to the previous figure, the outliers remain for Cyclistic members and each IQR overlaps which is an indication of no significant difference despite being categorized by day of the week.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"trip_data_cleaned %>%\n    group_by(day_of_week, member_casual) %>%\n    summarise(\n        min = min(ride_duration, trim = 0.05),\n        q25 = quantile(ride_duration, 0.25, trim = 0.05),\n        median = median(ride_duration, trim = 0.05),\n        mean = mean(ride_duration, trim = 0.05),\n        q75 = quantile(ride_duration, 0.75, trim = 0.05),\n        max = max(ride_duration, trim = 0.05),\n        iqr = q75 - q25\n    )","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-09-27T07:03:57.066922Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-09-27T07:03:57.068813Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-09-27T07:03:58.009150Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":"ggplot(data = trimmed_df, aes(x = day_of_week, y = ride_duration, fill = member_casual)) +\n    geom_boxplot(, position = \"dodge\") +\n    labs(x = \"Day of week\", y = \"Time in Minutes\", fill = \"User Type\", title = \"Ride Duration Distribution by Day of the Week\", tag = \"Figure 6\", caption = \"Data Source: Motivate International Inc.\") +\n    scale_y_continuous(labels = function(y) format(y, scientific = FALSE)) +\n    scale_fill_manual(values = c(\"casual\" = \"#e2bc2d\", \"member\" = \"#b067ce\")) ","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-09-27T07:03:58.013219Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-09-27T07:03:58.015381Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-09-27T07:04:14.513180Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# Share Phase\nOne of the deliverables for the sharing phase is data visualizations that convey clear meaning. This was achieved through the use of contextual elements such as headlines, labels, tags, and captions. These elements were designed with accessibility in mind and utilized color pairings that follow the Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG). They have been included in the analysis phase above to better organize the notebook.\n### Key Findings \nThe questions below are used to orient the second deliverable which are key findings from the analysis:\n> * Were you able to answer the question how annual members and casual riders use Cyclistic bikes differently?\n> * What story does your data tell?\n> * How do your findings relate to your original question?\n\n⭐ Cyclistic members outnumber casual riders by 26% from August 2022 to July 2023.\n\n⭐ Additionally, members consistently ride more proportionately by season, beginning from Spring through Winter with percentages of 32%, 14%, 26%, and 56%.\n\n⭐ Casual riders and Cyclistic members utilize different types of bikes. Casual riders do not have a preference between classic bikes and electric bikes, whereas Cyclistic members have a greater preference for classic bikes.\n\n⭐ Based on the count of casual riders per day of the week, they ride more on weekends than on weekdays, while Cyclistic members use Cyclistic’s services more during the weekdays compared to their count on the weekend.\n\n⭐ Cyclistic members also have shorter ride duration averages, about 7 minutes less, and less variability compared to the mean and variability of casual riders' ride durations.\n\n⭐ Casual riders have longer ride duration averages based on the means, compared to Cyclistic members who maintain shorter ride duration averages throughout the week.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# Act Phase\n### My Top 3 Recommendations based on the Analysis\n1. **Promote Seasonal Benefits:** Highlight the seasonal advantages of being a Cyclistic member, such as the consistent access to bikes even during peak seasons when there are bike shortages. This would be in addition to the higher availability of bikes across all seasons. This would emphasize an advantage of having a membership. \n\n2. **Weekday Promotions:** Implement weekday-specific promotions for Cyclistic members. Since they use the service more during weekdays, offer discounted rates or special benefits on weekdays to incentivize casual riders to become members.\n\n3. **Personalize the Membership Experience:** Ensure that discounts are available to Cyclistic members, including exclusive offers that reflect their usage trends. Customize discounts and promotions based on the individual usage frequency and bike preferences of each Cyclistic member.\n\n\nBy designing conversion strategies to the preferences and patterns of casual riders and emphasizing the advantages of Cyclistic membership, the likelihood of converting casual riders into Cyclistic members can increase.","metadata":{}}]}